commit.message:
Add a release target

The most important thing about this is not to forget
to run `build` before `sdist` to ensure the .c file is part
of the source package.

Add a target for testing the package from the source distribution

As a drive-by fix, this commit also tests the README synopsis.
Bump version for uploading re-cythonized .c source

Bump version 0.6.1 for re-upload

Hopefully, this fixes #2.

Add LICENSE to root repository

The license was already specified in the `setup.py` but it's
better to be very explicit.

Mention Fenwick tree and link to wikipedia

I only recently found out the name for this data structure in
the published literature.
CircleCI: test on multiple python versions

Tag version 0.6

Only difference is that the "source" distribution now contains
accumulation_tree.c cythonized with a later version of cython,
for compatibility with Python3.7+. See here for details:

https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/1978

and also #1.
Add CircleCI shield to README.md
Add circleCI continuous integration configuration
Link to tdigest and bintrees in the README

Bump to version 0.5

News: Now with the MIT licence.

Update metadata to production/stable since we have a downstream now

Doesn't really reflect a change in code quality, but it does
reflect a promise w.r.t. API stability.

Re-license to MIT

As the copyright holder of everything expect what is included in
c7ca38aff1756db1ed, I can do this, given that that commit includes an
MIT licenced project. It is needed because this library is intended
for use in `tdigest`, which is MIT licenced.
Add a synopsis to the readme
Remove version number from readme, since I forgot to update it three consecutive versions
Release v0.4
Enable serialization through 'cloudpickle'
Release v0.3

Remove reading long_description from file

I don't always have control over how setup.py is run; in particular,
I ran into:

    virtualenv --python=`which python3` env
    Already using interpreter /usr/bin/python3
    Using base prefix '/usr'
    New python executable in /home/tkluck/src/tdigest/env/bin/python3
    Also creating executable in /home/tkluck/src/tdigest/env/bin/python
    Installing setuptools, pkg_resources, pip, wheel...done.
    Obtaining file:///home/tkluck/src/tdigest
    Collecting bintrees (from tdigest==0.4.1.0)
    Collecting pyudorandom (from tdigest==0.4.1.0)
    Collecting accumulation_tree (from tdigest==0.4.1.0)
      Downloading accumulation_tree-0.2.tar.gz
        Complete output from command python setup.py egg_info:
        Traceback (most recent call last):
          File "<string>", line 1, in <module>
          File "/tmp/pip-build-9uhtos42/accumulation-tree/setup.py", line 15, in <module>
            long_description=read('README.md'),
          File "/tmp/pip-build-9uhtos42/accumulation-tree/setup.py", line 5, in read
            return open(os.path.join(os.path.dirname(__file__), fname)).read()
        FileNotFoundError: [Errno 2] No such file or directory: '/tmp/pip-build-9uhtos42/accumulation-tree/README.md'

        ----------------------------------------

While this is probably solvable, I don't care much about it
at this point.
Release v0.2
Add a doctest for updating a value (as opposed to just inserting
Migrate distutils -> setuptools for smoother cython support

Never mark 'fake' root keys as dirty

This prevents python 3 from complaining about 'unorderable types: int() and NoneType()'.

Include abctree.py and treeslice.py from bintrees into this project

The bintrees project states that it is deprecated on its github page. Since
accumulation_tree is closely intertwined with this software, it makes most
sense to just fork those parts we depend on. This also makes packaging easier.

These files are MIT-licensed, which is compatible with including these into a
GPL project.
Add a manifest file
Initial import into git
